pros:
- Good interaction with colleagues;
- Low-hierarchy people usually recognizes your good work (I mean, just the recognition itself );
- Good flexibility for working times, absences, etc
- Excellent pension plan

cons:
- Serious problems related to 'how to do' for nearly everything. Workflows are not properly defined, lots of confusions, everyone doing things following their own understanding;
- The company doesn't care about you, if you are happy or not with your job, there is no One-2-One meetings, no catch-ups. There is a huge gap between managers and employees;
- There is little or no investment in training or certification programs, at least for high skilled positions;
- Every single change, even those from your day-to-day job is very difficult and very slow to be authorized the implementation, often requiring 5 or more different approvals, many times by people that clearly are not prepared to take such decisions;
- There is little to no bonuses or profit participation, even though this is a financial company. It's a shame having less than 2% of your annual salary in a bonus that will be cut in half by taxes
